, it points to a faulty brake on that specific axis. If no brakes work, the 24V BRAKE power supply is likely missing.\\n4.  **Inspect Drive Module Power Supply:** Confirm that the 24V BRAKE voltage from the Drive Module power supply is correct.\\n5.  **Review Event Logs:** Check the event logs for any messages that could indicate other system faults keeping the brakes activated.\\n\\n**Important Safety Considerations:**\\n\\n*   **Secure the Robot Arm:** If there\'s any suspicion that the holding brakes are non-operational, the robot arm system must be secured by other means before any work is performed. Robot arms, especially on larger models, are heavy and can cause serious injury or damage if brakes fail.\\n*   **External Voltage Supply for Manual Release:** If intentionally disabling holding brakes with an external voltage supply, extreme caution is necessary. Never stand inside the robot\'s working area unless the arm is supported, and never stand beneath any of the robot\'s axes.\\n*   **Manual Brake Release:** For some robot models, there are specific procedures for manually releasing brakes using buttons on an internal brake release unit or by supplying power to a specific connector (e.g., R1.MP). However, be aware that incorrect connections can release all brakes simultaneously, leading to unexpected and rapid robot movements. Ensure no personnel are near or beneath the robot arm when performing a manual release.",\n    "Page Number": "",\n    "URL": "projects/338431745290/locations/global/collections/default_collection/dataStores/linamar-vector-bootcamp/branches/0/documents/abb-irc5-operating-troubleshooting-manual-p53"\n  },\n  {\n    "Document Name": "ABB_IRC5_Operating_Troubleshooting_Manual \\u2014 Page 51",\n    "Full Text": "When a robot\'s brakes fail to release, it can prevent any movement and trigger error messages. This issue can stem from several common problems related to electrical supply, control signals, or the physical brake components them