    *   **Excerpt:** \*\*Common Causes for Robot Brakes Not Releasing:\*\* \* \*\*Brake Contactor Malfunction:\*\* The brake contactor (e.g., K44 in ABB systems) might not be working correctly. This contactor is responsible for activating and deactivating the brakes. \* \*\*Incorrect \"Motors ON\" Status:\*\* The robot system may not be correctly registering the \"Motors ON\" status, which is a prerequisite for brake release. \* \*\*Faulty Brake on a Specific Axis:\*\* Individual brakes on one or more robot axes can be faulty. If only one brake malfunctions, that specific brake likely needs replacement. \* \*\*Missing 24V BRAKE Supply Voltage:\*\* A lack of the necessary 24V BRAKE power supply can prevent all brakes from releasing. \* \*\*Other System Faults:\*\* Various other faults within the robot system can cause the brakes to remain activated. In such cases, event log messages should provide additional diagnostic information. \* \*\*Oil Leaks:\*\* Oil leaking from a motor or gearbox can contaminate and lubricate the motor brake, causing it to fail to hold or release properly.
*   **Source:** ABB_IRC5_Operating_Troubleshooting_Manual
