<p>Grinding or scraping noises emanating from robot joints during operation are significant indicators of potential mechanical issues that require prompt attention. These noises often signal underlying problems that, if left unaddressed, can lead to decreased performance, inconsistent path accuracy, and ultimately, complete joint failure.</p>
<p><strong>Common Causes of Grinding or Scraping Noises:</strong></p>
<p>The primary culprits behind these alarming sounds in robot joints typically include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Worn Bearings:</strong> Bearings are critical components that allow for smooth motion. When they become worn, they can produce scraping, grinding, or clicking noises, often preceding their complete failure.</li>
<li><strong>Contamination:</strong> The presence of foreign particles or debris within the bearing races can cause scraping and grinding as the joint moves.</li>
<li><strong>Loss of Lubrication:</strong> Insufficient or degraded lubrication in bearings can lead to increased friction, generating grinding noises and accelerating wear.</li>
<li><strong>Gearbox Issues:</strong> If the noise originates from a gearbox, it could be due to overheating, incorrect oil quality or level, or a damaged mechanical joint between the motor and gearbox.</li>
<li><strong>Damaged Mechanical Joint (Motor to Gearbox):</strong> A compromised connection between the motor and gearbox can also result in noticeable noise.</li>
<li><strong>Brake Problems:</strong> Brakes that are not releasing correctly can also contribute to mechanical noise.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Consequences of Unaddressed Noise:</strong></p>
<p>Ignoring grinding or scraping noises can lead to severe consequences, including:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Inconsistent Path Accuracy:</strong> The robot may deviate from its programmed path.</li>
<li><strong>Production Interruption:</strong> The robot's operation may become impossible.</li>
<li><strong>Complete Joint Seizure:</strong> In severe cases, the affected joint can seize entirely, leading to significant downtime and repair costs.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Recommended Actions for Troubleshooting and Resolution:</strong></p>
<p>When such noises are detected, a systematic approach to diagnosis and repair is crucial:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Identify the Source:</strong> Pinpoint which specific bearing, motor, or gearbox is emitting the noise.</li>
<li><strong>Check Lubrication:</strong> Ensure that the bearings and gearboxes have adequate and appropriate lubrication as specified in the product manual.</li>
<li><strong>Inspect for Wear and Damage:</strong>
<ul>
<li>Examine bearings for wear and contamination. If possible, disassemble the joint to measure clearance.</li>
<li>Check for damage to the mechanical joint between the motor and gearbox.</li>
<li>Inspect balancing devices for dissonance, which can manifest as a tapping sound.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><strong>Consider Gearbox Health:</strong> If the noise is from the gearbox, check the oil level and quality, and investigate for overheating.</li>
<li><strong>Evaluate Calibration:</strong> Incorrect robot calibration or TCP (Tool Center Point) definition can sometimes be associated with noise and inconsistent path accuracy, though this is often a secondary symptom.</li>
<li><strong>Replace Faulty Components:</strong> Bearings inside motors are typically not replaced individually; the entire motor is replaced. Faulty bearings or motors should be replaced according to the product manual.</li>
<li><strong>Review Event Logs:</strong> Check the robot's event logs for messages that might indicate the cause of the issue, such as "Joint load too high" or "Joint collision".</li>
</ol>
<p>Always observe safety information, especially concerning potentially hot robot components, before performing any inspections or maintenance.</p>
<p><em>Source: ABB_IRC5_Operating_Troubleshooting_Manual — Page 50</em></p>
