 to the product manual for... <truncated>
An unresponsive robot controller and FlexPendant can be caused by a number of issues, ranging from simple power supply problems to more complex software or hardware failures. Here is a systematic guide to help you diagnose and resolve the issue.

### 1. Initial Checks for Power and Connection

The first step is to check the basics of the power supply and the physical connection of the FlexPendant.

*   **Verify Power Supply:** Ensure that the robot controller is properly connected to the main power supply and that the voltage level is correct. Check that the main transformer is properly connected and that the main fuse (Q1) in the Drive Module has not tripped.
*   **Check Main Switches:** Make sure that all main switches are turned on.
*   **FlexPendant Connection:** Check that the FlexPendant is securely connected to the controller. The connector is usually located on the operator's panel. Inspect the connector for any dirt or damage before connecting it.
*   **FlexPendant Cable Integrity:** Examine the FlexPendant cable for any visible damage. A faulty cable should be replaced.
*   **Test with Another FlexPendant:** If you have access to another FlexPendant, try connecting it to the controller to rule out the possibility that the FlexPendant itself or its cable is the source of the problem.
*   **Test FlexPendant on another Controller:** If you have access to another controller, you can test the FlexPendant on it to determine if the issue is with the FlexPendant or the original controller.

### 2. Controller-Specific Troubleshooting

If the FlexPendant appears to be connected but the controller is still unresponsive, you should focus on the controller itself.

*   **Controller Not Responding (LEDs Not Lit):** If the controller's LED indicators are not lit, it is likely a power issue.
    *   Ensure that the main power supply is working and is within the specified limits.
    *   Check if the main fuse (Q1) in the Drive Module has tripped.
    *   Verify the connection between the Control and Drive modules.
*   **Check Power Supply Units:** Confirm that the power supply to both the Control and Drive modules is within the specified limits. If necessary, troubleshoot the power supply units.
*   **Check Indication LEDs:** Observe all the indication LEDs on the controller units and consult the manual to understand their meaning.
*   **Main Computer Issues:** Problems with the main computer within the controller can lead to an unresponsive FlexPendant, even if it appears to be starting up.

### 3. FlexPendant Software and Communication Issues

Even if the FlexPendant starts, it may not be able to communicate correctly or display a screen image.

*   **FlexPendant Starts, No Screen Image:** This could indicate issues with the Ethernet network or the main computer.
    *   Check all the cables from the power supply unit to the main computer.
    *   Ensure that the FlexPendant is correctly connected to the controller.
    *   Review the indication LEDs and status signals on the main computer.
*   **Reset FlexPendant:** If the FlexPendant freezes during operation, you can press the reset button on its back to restart it. Note that this will only reset the FlexPendant, not the controller system.
*   **Firmware Mismatch:** If the RobotWare on the controller has been upgraded, the FlexPendant will automatically reflash its firmware when it is connected. If this process is interrupted by switching off the controller, it can cause issues. An incompatible firmware version in a Profinet PCI board can also prevent communication.

### 4. Advanced Troubleshooting and System Restart

If the basic checks do not resolve the issue, you may need to take more advanced steps.

*   **Systematic Troubleshooting:** When you are replacing components, do so one at a time to identify the faulty part. Always refer to the product manual for detailed repair instructions.
*   **Check for Loose Connections/Damage:** Inspect all attachment screws, connectors, and cabling for security and damage. Make sure that the units are clean.
*   **Controller Restart:**
    *   **Restart:** This will restart the system and save all programs and configurations.
    *   **Restart and Start Boot Application:** This is used to select another system or if the RobotWare system is unable to start up.
    *   **Restart and Reset RAPID:** This will delete all user-loaded RAPID programs and cannot be undone.
    *   **Restart and Reset System:** This will return the system to its default settings.
*   **Event Log:** Check the event log for any messages that might indicate the root cause of the problem.

If the problem persists after you have performed these steps, it is recommended that you contact ABB support. Be sure to provide them with the robot's serial number, the RobotWare version, any external options, a detailed description of the fault, and any diagnostic files or event logs.

