 remain pressurized after power shutdown must have clearly visible drain facilities and warning signs. Pressure must be released from pneumatic or hydraulic systems before repairs, and only personnel with special knowledge should work on hydraulic equipment.\\n    *   **Mechanical:** Be aware that axes are affected by gravity when brakes are released, posing a risk of being hit or crushed by moving robot parts, especially the parallel arm. Energy stored for counterbalancing certain axes may be released during dismantling. Take measures to prevent the robot from collapsing when parts are removed, such as securing the lower arm if removing the axis-2 motor.\\n*   **Hot Surfaces** Motors and gearboxes can become very hot after the robot has been running, posing a burn risk. Avoid touching these components.\\n*   **Falling Objects** When dismantling or assembling mechanical units, be vigilant for falling objects.\\n*   **No Climbing** Never use the robot as a ladder or climb on its motors or other parts during service, as there is a serious risk of slipping due to high temperatures and potential oil spills.\\n*   **First Test Run Precautions** After any service activity involving disassembly, follow a strict procedure for the first test run. Remove all service tools and foreign objects, verify the robot is secured, ensure all safety equipment installed during service is removed, and confirm that the fixture and workpiece are secured. All personnel must stand at a safe distance behind safety fences. Pay close attention to the function of the serviced part during this test.\\n*   **Brake Release Buttons** After service work involving the SMB recess, verify that brake release buttons are not jammed in the depressed position before turning on power. A jammed button will release the motor brake, which can cause serious injury or damage.\\n*   **Personal Protective Equipment (PPE)** Always use appropriate PPE based on the risk assessment for the specific robot installation.\\n*   **Protective Earth** ... <truncated>
Before servicing the IRB 8700 robot, it is crucial to take several safety precautions to ensure the safety of personnel and prevent damage to the equipment. Here are the key measures to follow:

### **Personnel and Workspace Safety**
*   **Qualified Personnel Only:** Only technicians trained by ABB who fully understand the robot's operation should perform maintenance or repairs.
*   **Establish Safety Zones:** Before entering the robot's working area, set up safety zones using barriers, light beams, or sensitive mats to prevent unauthorized access.
*   **Accessible Emergency Stops:** Ensure that emergency stop buttons are easily accessible to quickly halt the robot's movement if needed.

### **Energy Isolation (Lockout/Tagout)**
*   **Electrical Power:** Completely turn off all electrical power to the robot and controller. The main switch on the controller cabinet should be locked out to prevent accidental reconnection. Be aware of stored electrical energy in components like capacitors.
*   **Pneumatic/Hydraulic Systems:** Release all pressure from pneumatic or hydraulic systems. These components can remain pressurized even after the main power is off.
*   **Mechanical Energy:** Be cautious of stored mechanical energy. Axes can move unexpectedly due to gravity when brakes are released. If removing heavy components like the axis-2 motor, ensure the robot arm is properly secured to prevent it from collapsing.

### **Physical Hazard Awareness**
*   **Hot Surfaces:** Motors and gearboxes can become extremely hot during operation. Allow them to cool down before touching them to avoid burns.
*   **Falling Objects:** Be vigilant for falling parts and tools when assembling or dismantling mechanical units.
*   **Do Not Climb:** Never use the robot as a ladder. Surfaces may be slippery from oil, and high temperatures pose a burn risk.

### **Post-Service Procedures**
*   **First Test Run:** After service is complete, conduct a test run with extreme caution.
    *   Remove all tools and foreign objects from the work area.
    *   Ensure the robot, fixtures, and workpiece are properly secured.
    *   All personnel must be outside the safety fences.
    *   Pay close attention to the function of the serviced part during the test.
*   **Check Brake Release Buttons:** Ensure that any manual brake release buttons are not stuck in the depressed position before restoring power. A jammed button can cause an axis to move unexpectedly.

### **General Precautions**
*   **Personal Protective Equipment (PPE):** Always wear the appropriate PPE as determined by a risk assessment of the task.
*   **Protective Earth:** Verify that the robot is properly connected to protective earth before starting any work.

Always consult the official IRB 8700 Product Manual for comprehensive safety information before performing any service.

